 {"id":"DIAL-fxu","title":"Audio Tick Feedback (Haptic Simulation)","description":"# Description

Implement optional audio tick feedback that plays a subtle click sound on each volume step change, providing haptic-like feedback for the wireless Surface Dial.

## Background & Rationale

### The Problem
The Surface Dial provides excellent haptic feedback when used on-screen (via Surface Studio), but when used wirelessly as a standalone Bluetooth device:
- No physical feedback on rotation (smooth, frictionless)
- Users can't tell if their input is registering without looking at screen
- Easy to over-rotate or under-rotate

Physical volume knobs on audio equipment have detents (click stops). The Surface Dial lacks these when wireless.

### Why This Matters
1. **Confirms input** — Know your rotation registered without looking
2. **Precision control** — Hear each step, know exactly how much you turned
3. **Accessibility** — Users with visual impairments benefit from audio feedback
4. **Professional feel** — Matches high-end audio equipment behavior
5. **Easy to implement** — Just play a short sound file

### Design Decision
- Play a subtle tick sound (50-100ms) on each volume step
- Different sound for:
  - Normal step
  - Boundary hit (0% or 100%)
  - Mode change
  - Mute toggle
- Must not be annoying — subtle, short, configurable volume
- Must be FAST — no perceptible latency

## Implementation Details

### Sound Files
```
resources/sounds/
├── tick.wav        # Normal volume step (~50ms, subtle click)
├── boundary.wav    # Hit 0% or 100% (~100ms, slightly different tone)
├── mode.wav        # Mode change (~150ms, two-tone)
└── mute.wav        # Mute toggle (~100ms, distinctive)
```

Embed sounds in binary or load from config directory.

### Audio Playback

```rust
// src/audio/feedback.rs

use rodio::{Decoder, OutputStream, OutputStreamHandle, Sink};
use std::io::Cursor;
use std::sync::Arc;

/// Audio feedback system for haptic-like sounds
pub struct AudioFeedback {
    _stream: OutputStream,
    handle: OutputStreamHandle,
    sounds: FeedbackSounds,
    config: FeedbackConfig,
}

struct FeedbackSounds {
    tick: Arc<[u8]>,
    boundary: Arc<[u8]>,
    mode_change: Arc<[u8]>,
    mute: Arc<[u8]>,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
pub struct FeedbackConfig {
    pub enabled: bool,
    pub volume: f32,           // 0.0 - 1.0
    pub tick_enabled: bool,
    pub boundary_enabled: bool,
    pub mode_enabled: bool,
    pub mute_enabled: bool,
}

impl Default for FeedbackConfig {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            enabled: true,
            volume: 0.3,  // Subtle by default
            tick_enabled: true,
            boundary_enabled: true,
            mode_enabled: true,
            mute_enabled: true,
        }
    }
}

impl AudioFeedback {
    pub fn new(config: FeedbackConfig) -> Result<Self, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        let (stream, handle) = OutputStream::try_default()?;

        // Embed sounds at compile time
        let sounds = FeedbackSounds {
            tick: Arc::from(include_bytes!("../../resources/sounds/tick.wav").as_slice()),
            boundary: Arc::from(include_bytes!("../../resources/sounds/boundary.wav").as_slice()),
            mode_change: Arc::from(include_bytes!("../../resources/sounds/mode.wav").as_slice()),
            mute: Arc::from(include_bytes!("../../resources/sounds/mute.wav").as_slice()),
        };

        Ok(Self {
            _stream: stream,
            handle,
            sounds,
            config,
        })
    }

    fn play_sound(&self, data: &Arc<[u8]>) {
        if !self.config.enabled {
            return;
        }

        let cursor = Cursor::new(data.clone());
        if let Ok(source) = Decoder::new(cursor) {
            let sink = Sink::try_new(&self.handle).ok();
            if let Some(sink) = sink {
                sink.set_volume(self.config.volume);
                sink.append(source);
                sink.detach();  // Play in background, don't block
            }
        }
    }

    /// Play tick sound for normal volume step
    pub fn tick(&self) {
        if self.config.tick_enabled {
            self.play_sound(&self.sounds.tick);
        }
    }

    /// Play boundary sound when hitting 0% or 100%
    pub fn boundary(&self) {
        if self.config.boundary_enabled {
            self.play_sound(&self.sounds.boundary);
        }
    }

    /// Play mode change sound
    pub fn mode_change(&self) {
        if self.config.mode_enabled {
            self.play_sound(&self.sounds.mode_change);
        }
    }

    /// Play mute toggle sound
    pub fn mute_toggle(&self) {
        if self.config.mute_enabled {
            self.play_sound(&self.sounds.mute);
        }
    }

    /// Update configuration (e.g., from config file reload)
    pub fn update_config(&mut self, config: FeedbackConfig) {
        self.config = config;
    }
}
```

### Daemon Integration

```rust
// In src/daemon.rs

impl Daemon {
    fn handle_rotation(&mut self, direction: i8) {
        let old_volume = self.get_current_volume();

        // ... adjust volume ...

        let new_volume = self.get_current_volume();

        // Play appropriate feedback sound
        if let Some(feedback) = &self.audio_feedback {
            if new_volume == 0 || new_volume == 100 {
                feedback.boundary();
            } else if new_volume != old_volume {
                feedback.tick();
            }
            // If volume didn't change (already at boundary), no sound
        }
    }

    fn handle_click(&mut self, click_type: ClickResult) {
        if let Some(feedback) = &self.audio_feedback {
            match click_type {
                ClickResult::SingleClick => feedback.mute_toggle(),
                ClickResult::DoubleClick => feedback.mode_change(),
                _ => {}
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Custom Sound Support

```rust
impl AudioFeedback {
    /// Load custom sounds from user config directory
    pub fn load_custom_sounds(config_dir: &Path) -> Option<FeedbackSounds> {
        let sounds_dir = config_dir.join("sounds");
        if !sounds_dir.exists() {
            return None;
        }

        Some(FeedbackSounds {
            tick: Self::load_sound_file(&sounds_dir.join("tick.wav"))?,
            boundary: Self::load_sound_file(&sounds_dir.join("boundary.wav"))?,
            mode_change: Self::load_sound_file(&sounds_dir.join("mode.wav"))?,
            mute: Self::load_sound_file(&sounds_dir.join("mute.wav"))?,
        })
    }

    fn load_sound_file(path: &Path) -> Option<Arc<[u8]>> {
        std::fs::read(path).ok().map(|v| Arc::from(v.into_boxed_slice()))
    }
}
```

## Configuration Options

```toml
[audio_feedback]
enabled = true              # Master enable/disable
volume = 0.3                # Feedback sound volume (0.0-1.0)

[audio_feedback.sounds]
tick = true                 # Play on each volume step
boundary = true             # Play when hitting 0% or 100%
mode_change = true          # Play on mode switch
mute = true                 # Play on mute toggle

# Optional: custom sound files
# custom_sounds_dir = "~/.config/surface-dial/sounds"
```

## Sound Design Guidelines

For the default sounds:
- **tick.wav**: Short (30-50ms), subtle click. Think keyboard key press, not mouse click. Low-mid frequency. Volume normalized to -20dB.
- **boundary.wav**: Slightly longer (80-100ms), different character. Could be two quick ticks or a soft "thunk". Indicates "you can't go further".
- **mode.wav**: Two-tone (150ms total). Rising tone for entering mode, could be reversed for exiting. Distinctive but not jarring.
- **mute.wav**: Single tone (100ms). Different character from tick. Could be a soft "swoosh" or "pop".

All sounds should:
- Be royalty-free or created fresh
- Have fast attack (no fade-in)
- Be normalized to similar perceived loudness
- Work well at low volumes

## Dependencies

- `rodio` crate for cross-platform audio playback
- Config storage (DIAL-mms) - for feedback settings
- Daemon refactor (DIAL-l6g) - integration point

